article.description:
Bo Outlaw had season highs of 19 points and 15
rebounds to help the Phoenix Suns improve their playoff chances
with a 111-94 victory over the Minnesota Timberwolves on Saturday.
article.headline: T-Wolves fall game behind Blazers for No. 4 spot
article.linkText: Suns pound T-Wolves to gain ground on idle Rockets
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Bo Outlaw always brings energy off the bench. In this game, he brought plenty of points and rebounds, too.
Outlaw

Outlaw had season highs of 19 points and 15 rebounds, his first double-double in nearly two years with Phoenix, as the Suns improved their playoff chances with a 111-94 victory over the Minnesota Timberwolves on Saturday. "This was a big game,'' Outlaw said. "The rest of our games are big. We've got to come and play with an attitude.'' The Suns, who beat the Timberwolves for the first time in four tries this season, have won four of five overall to boost their lead to 1½ games over idle Houston for the eighth and final playoff spot in the West with seven to play. "For us, we've just got to win,'' Stephon Marbury said. "If we win, we control our own destiny. It doesn't matter what Houston does.'' The Timberwolves have lost four of five to fall a game behind Portland for the No. 4 spot in the West and home-court advantage in the first round of the playoffs. Minnesota plays at Portland Sunday night. "There's no way we should have lost like this,'' Kevin Garnett said. "We're coming down the line and the playoffs are right around the corner and we're not playing so well. We've got to find a way to come out of this slump and come out of it quick.'' Outlaw, Phoenix's energizer off the bench, went 6-for-10 from the field and 7-for-8 from the free throw line. He also had three blocked shots and five assists. "Every shot I scored on was not an individual move. It was a pass from one of my teammates,'' Outlaw said. "I was moving and they found me. I give the credit to those guys.'' Shawn Marion scored 24 and Marbury 23 for Phoenix. Penny Hardaway added 14 points and nine assists. Amare Stoudemire scored 10, all in the third quarter on 5-for-5 shooting. Jake Voskuhl had eight points and 10 rebounds as Phoenix dominated the boards 49-38. Voskuhl brings almost as much of a spark off the bench as Outlaw does. "That's what me and Jake do,'' Outlaw said. "We try to bring energy and aggressiveness on defense. That's us.'' The Suns frustrated the Timberwolves with a double-teaming zone defense, and as always, Marbury gave his opponents fits with his penetration. "Steph has always been difficult for us,'' Minnesota coach Flip Saunders said. "He's very aggressive, and if there's one thing, that's our weakness the last few years. We aren't geared towards guarding players one-on-one.'' Garnett had 25 points and 17 rebounds for the Timberwolves, who allowed over 110 points for the fourth time in five games. Wally Szczerbiak added 23 points, Troy Hudson 16 and Anthony Peeler 14 for Minnesota. Minnesota, 24-for-24 at the foul line, sank five free throws in a row, the last two by Szczerbiak, to take its only lead of the second half, 59-58, with 8:05 left in the third quarter. The Timberwolves were down just 66-65 after Troy Hudson's two free throws with 4:21 to go in the third. But the Suns went on a 15-4 run to take an 81-69 lead on Marbury's three-point play and were up 85-73 going into the final quarter. Phoenix maintained a double-digit lead throughout the final quarter. Outlaw scored six in a row, including two free throws that nullified two of his misses, to give the Suns a 104-88 lead with 3:48 to play. Marion's 3-pointer put Phoenix ahead 107-90 with 3:09 remaining. The 17-point lead, then and at the finish, was the Suns' largest. Game notes
The Suns' reserves outscored their Minnesota counterparts 32-8. ... The Suns began a stretch of four games in six days. They play the Lakers in Los Angeles Sunday night. ... The last time the Timberwolves played the Suns, March 9 in Phoenix, Garnett had a triple-double with 29 points, 14 rebounds and 12 assists. ... For the first time this season, the Suns started a three-guard lineup of Marbury, Hardaway and Joe Johnson, along with Marion and Stoudemire. ... Phoenix was 19-of-20 from the foul line.
